annotation.TEXT: Aim your jumps carefully, and don't forget about the two-space offset or the low ceiling.
Yep, we're nearing the end of the game, folks! To be continued...
And now let's climb up here and enter door number 1...
Okay, now remember this pattern for later. There's a row of three ? blocks, followed by a pit with a cement block over it.
...Yeah, you can see the gimmick now. This is really neat.
Fireballs and enemy placements can still help you out if you're getting confused.
Note: If you jump towards the bat too soon, it might fly too high to reach with your pogo bounce, so wait until it stops ascending before you jump towards it.
Fortunately, the enemies can be very helpful in showing you where some solid objects are.
Oh, and the random level ending in "-1" isn't really random. (And the other random level had no chance of affecting the outcome here.)
Also, I still hate that glitch with the annotations not disappearing at the right time in the editor! It's such an annoying bother!

Oh, but I think I remember that the ON/OFF block must turned OFF like this. Now, let's enter door number Life, the Universe, and Everything over here. (Did simply entering that door require the switch to be OFF when raocow played?)
Now, if you hit this P-switch right where you find it, stuff appears!
Okay, now over here... Hmm... Has part of this room changed since raocow played it?
You can get through this ? block wall by cape spinning it or throwing the second P-switch at it. Cape spinning is easier, and there are power up blocks with capes in this level.
Well, I can get a feather here. And, if I go all the way to the right, I can get a star coin.
Hello, and welcome back to Super Marina World. I thought I'd mess with the speed of the footage here, just to be random. Now, let's take a look at those votes...
So, wait for Dracula Duck to appear and summon a small bat, then cane pogo bounce off of the bat so that you can hit him.
I guess the official name is "Trimmed World".
Huh. Well, there's a shell, which I should probably take with me.

This screen with these cut-and-paste ? blocks is what I wanted to choose as a video thumbnail, but I think YouTube's being a pain with that right now, and keeps reverting to a thumbnail showing a later part of this level.
May as well win this very easy race against Glomgold while I'm here. (If you somehow lose the race, the game ultimately treats it as if you lost a life and you'll have to defeat Dracula Duck again.)
Okay, now we get even trickier. The stuff below is offset two spaces horizontally from the stuff above. You must keep this in mind for the entirety of this part.
Aww... But I can't enter door number 4 yet, not with the ON/OFF switches in their current state. So, let's enter door number 1 again.
Pogo bounce off of Dracula Duck five times to defeat him (just like all the other bosses in this game).
Alright, now in this room, you've gotta dodge a few Eeries. Hmm... There's a yellow block there that I can't reach. I think I'll need a weapon to throw at the gray blocks surrounding it...
Whoa, how did I not get roasted there? I guess the flame's hit box wasn't actually active yet.
And, door number 3 also just sends you back to start. So, let's go back up there and see what's to the left.
Now, this part is interesting. I travel through the "pasted" part here, and have to remember the terrain here for later.
Here's another cut-and-paste thing. Watch out for the pit! Having fireballs can be very useful in this level to help verify where land is.

There's a ? block bridge leading to the left to this 1♥P (though it's easily reachable from riding a winged block anyway). And, to the right, there's another ? block bridge with a load of coins above it. Can I get them all?
Alright, that's all of the star coins, so I don't need to worry about those anymore. Now to hit this ON/OFF block in order to enter door number Superstar Saga...

There's also a star coin in that box. Huh, I think this cut-and-paste box is actually slightly inaccurate. The upper two rows of the checkerboard on the right should extend one space further to the right.
Also, the recycled vote is interesting in that one of the level choices this time is a ghost house, so it counts towards that.
Oh, yeah. I remember this place from when raocow did it. It's a tricky puzzle involving P-switches and doors. Well, let's start by hitting this P-switch and going left...
Yeah, it tries to trick you there.

That took way more hits than it should've (probably because I was hitting the block too rapidly). Oh, and I don't enter door number The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy here, but it just sends you back to the level's start.
Alright, just taking one more look at that. Now, let's "feel" my way through...
Now, this is neat. See the blank checkerboard box to the right, and the checkerboard box above that has coins and a ? block?
Yes, just in time! Oh, and I checked the rest of the level with the P-switch off screen, and didn't find any other special use for it.
Bonus game average so far: 238 / 33 = 7.212 1♥Ps each.
Goal tape average so far: 3422 / 87 = 39.333 stars each.
Okay, more munchers to deal with. Also, be careful of the low ceiling here.

And, we're done! Bah, that was a lame goal tape hit. It's been a long time since I last had a hit below 30 (or even below 40). Oh, but at least I got in just before the "Hurry up!" warning could occur!
BGM: Uirdz - Secret Level
Don't forget about that wall of cement in the air right here.
Huh. So, there's a P-switch up there, which requires you to hit the ON/OFF block near the start of the room multiple times in a row to get. I'll get to that later.
Okay, so here I am in the NES Ducktales, and it's final boss time, against Dracula Duck himself!
That revealed a vine, which I'll climb up in just a few seconds here...
Hmm... Was there not a shell in this room in the past, that was used to hit this ON/OFF block? Or am I remembering wrong?
And now for 7-6, which came in second in the voting.
So, yeah. We've got 8-B Star Athletics, and 8-3 Evil Star Hill. Place your votes for one of them, and that'll determine where I go next time!
Also, there are plenty of Dino Rhino Bino Linos here. Uh, oh. The next cut-and-paste box contains munchers.
Oh, before I enter door number The Restaurant at the End of the Universe, let's see what's over here to the left...
And, there's goal number Gnarly!
Alright, if you spin jump off of this bubble, you can bounce up here to reach a P-switch and door number 3. There is more stuff to the left, which I'll get to in a moment.

Ha! Sneak attack from the rear! If Dracula Duck appears above your head and not near a wall, try going behind him quickly. If the small bat follows, you can bounce off it sooner and not have to worry about it going too high on you.
Alright, now that world 7 is clear, all that remains is world 8, and there are only two levels to pick from now.
And that unlocks a path leading to 7-7. I don't think there was a secret exit in 7-6, but if there is, let me know! Now, before I forget, I've gotta revisit 7-5 just to show off something.
Alright, now that the winners have been decided, let's get out of slow-mo mode here...
And this leads to door number Partners in Time, which I'll enter as soon as I glitch the shell onto the roof.
Which means, I can now enter door number 4 up here!
Oh, and you can jump onto the pasted box here, but there's no real point in doing so.
Oh, what? I'm sent back to start again? Yep, but with a very important difference this time. You see, that was the only way I could get into the starting room with the switches in the OFF position.

And there you go. Completing Photoshop Plains (7-B Trimmed World) takes you back to 3-3. Yep, that's about it. (Might be useful if you previously skipped over world 3 by going straight from world 2 to world 5 earlier.)

Alright, now if I hit this ON/OFF block here repeatedly, that P-switch above the top of the screen (which I got a glimpse of earlier) should come on down! You're the next contestant on The Price is Right! ...Wait, this isn't a game show here.
Alright, let's bounce off of these cut-and-paste note blocks. Pay attention, as the last note block is offset by one space horizontally.
Oddly, the Mega Mole can move through the apparent lower part of the cannon... Also, the floor the Mega Mole is walking on is made of munchers, so don't fall.
Nuts, only got 30 here. Man, today has not been very good for my goal tape average...
Note: There was a late vote for Super Mario Crossover, so pretend that "1" in the upper-left corner is a "2".
Once again, the enemies can help you determine where stuff is.
Oh, ha, ha. I like how this was even done with the midpoint.
Ah, I'm back in the Eerie room, but now I've got a shell that I can use to destroy these gray blocks, allowing me to hit the yellow block.
And now let's head on over to 7-B, which raocow called "Photoshop Plains". You'll see why in just a few seconds!
Meh. I guess I'll just take the mushroom, rather than struggle with trying to avoid it. Also, be aware that the darker checkerboard above acts as a ceiling to the player.

Sorry, I couldn't think of any video game where you climb Mount Vesuvius off the top of my head. (UPDATE: Mt. Vesuvius is the final level in Ducktales Remastered, which I wasn't aware of when I first made this video.)
Alright, pay careful attention to the upper half of the screen here, as it corresponds to the lower half.
Um, yeah. Door number 2 just leads back to start.
Now, I tried looking for a picture of Fracktail fractals, but didn't find any, which is a bummer...
Okay, now I believe I hit the P-switch here, which causes some ? blocks to appear.
So, where will door number 4 take me?
Goal tape average so far: 3392 / 86 = 39.442 stars each.
Aww... That just led back to start. Well, let's go to the right this time...
And that's game!
Another inaccuracy: That four-tile tall cannon on the left up there is one tile too short down here. (Though it fires from the correct spot.)
